title: What I did not see coming after retirement.
description: What I did not see coming after retirement.
transcript_text: Were you aware before you decided to retire and retired, how difficult retirement would be? It's funny, the way my mind works is like a sense of cope. I'm like, I know it's gonna be hard, but I don't know what's gonna come. And I think what I thought I was going to miss was, like, being mr. Olympia, getting on stage, prep, all the things in between. But one of the moments where it hit me really hard, and I'm not even proud to admit this, is that I went on Instagram and I looked at my followers and it was like, last month you decreased 10,000. And I was like, oh, I've had this feeling in my body that I didn't like that. I've told myself for a decade that I don't give a fuck about that, but it's easy to say when it's just constant skyrocket up, like, I don't care about the success, I'm not attached to this. And all of a sudden, it was like, not there. It just made me really go inside and be like, what? What was I doing it for? What did I really care about? What was like, the have to. Is that I had to do it to be good enough. Was it because of the attention and all the stuff? Before it was like, the love of the sport, it was love of bodybuilding. And then it became this attachment to this, like, need of, like, what came With it all those stuff are incredible. Don't get me wrong, it's not like my don't value having money and attention. Like I'm human, I enjoy it. But it's not what was making me feel good day today. It was taking away from my ability to be at home and I would be like, I have to eat again. I missed a meal, I came to an event, I lost a pound. Are my legs big enough this year? I feel like my waist got bigger. Like, am I gonna be good enough to be the best in the world? That pulls you away from being present in your day to day life cause you're constantly worrying about that. And that's because I became more attached to the outcome than just the love of the game.

title: Where to find self worth.
description: Where to find self worth.
transcript_text: Where do you think about self worth coming from post retirement? I would say by genuinely knowing and believing that I'm living up to what my most important values are. For example, if I wanna be a good father, if I know I'm showing up as being a good father, that's my value, that's within my control, then I feel good. But the difference of that of like, oh, I want my daughter to love me or be happy with me, or whatever it might be, something like that, is out of your control in the moment. And those are what I would worry for, where if my daughter looked at me, she's like, I hate you, dad, which probably will inevitably happen at some point. And then my self worth is attached to her not hating me. So then I have a crumble and I believe it, and then I act in a certain way rather than being able to dissociate with that and be like, what are my values? Being a good dad. Am I being a good dad? Yeah. Yes, I know I have been being a good dad myself. Worth isn't attached her not saying she hates me. It's in how I know I show up. Hmm. And in believing in my character and who I'm being. So when she says, I hate you, dad, I can not react to that and be able to be like, something's going on with her. What is she experiencing? And I don't have to have the selfish response of, well, I need to get her to love me now. It's like, no, she's hurting right now. Let me be there for her. I mean, that's the double cheat code of being a good dad and having controlled self worth, but learning to learn what your values are and live by them in a way that they're within your control. Hmm.

title: How to choose the right partner.
description: How to choose the right partner.
transcript_text: What's your advice for choosing a good partner? Before what you're looking out for, it's what you're putting out. What you put out, you attract. title: The benefits of adding Strongman training into your workout routine
description: The benefits of adding Strongman training into your workout routine
transcript_text: So we're throwing in some strongman stuff into my programming, which is the Jackson style. So what does it benefit the body? Essentially, it's like a five birds with one stone scenario. Instead of you sitting on a rower and improving your cardiovascular ability that way, we're doing it through strength training, predominantly concentric. So it's not creating as much of like a deficit for you to recover out of. But then as well for you, we're trying to make your back better, your core better, your hips better. So we're using movements and time under tension and rest periods that are gonna improve more than just you wanna lower resting heart rate. Like we're trying to make it to where this is also gonna benefit what you do in the gym. It's gonna benefit if you decide to go do something athletic. It's improving certain things that you can even argue like a standard bodybuilding workout wouldn't do. So it's a double dip in a lot of ways.

title: The Reality Of Bodybuilding
description: The Reality Of Bodybuilding
transcript_text: Bodybuilding is a very ego centric sport, very vain. It's just like intense and there's like almost like a stereotype that's very accurate of the way people are like trying to be better than the next guy, comparing to this guy. It's a comparison sport, it's subjective. You're being pageantry. And I think a lot of bodybuilders before me, they were like, you gotta be on stage, you gotta be stepping on the saying, you're gonna beat this guy. You see him, you know you're better than him. Be like that. When I was young, I was like, okay, that's how I have to be to win. But it didn't make me feel like I was getting better. If anything it stressed me out, it made me anxious cause I was comparing myself to others and like trying to be what they were. But especially in bodybuilding where it is so subjective, you have no control of what the judges do. So if you're trying to beat them or do what the judges do and the judges switch what they want, then you're just pissed cause you didn't do what you want. You might as well just be doing it for yourself, creating the body that you are proud of, that you think is the best, and being the best version of yourself. title: Often times difficult situations are the catalyst for your growth

transcript_text: When you eat right and you train hard, you get the result. And when you put yourself in difficult situations, you're forced to be in a place to grow mentally. But I knew how much I love the end result, and I knew when I consistently did it, the person it made me become. So I continued to push myself more and more, and every year was really, I guess, blessed to have a mindset where I was just looking at what was right in front of me. title: A journey of feeling powerless may actually be your greatest teacher
description: A journey of feeling powerless may actually be your greatest teacher
transcript_text: My journey started with something very health related. In 2018, before I ever won an Olympia, I got really sick. It was autoimmune to my kidneys, so I had this insane amount of inflammation, edema in my legs. I put on, like, 15 pounds in a day, and I had, like, no knee, no ankle. It was just inflamed. I didn't know what was going on. I was put in the hospital, put on loop diuretics, IV diuretics, and all stuff just to get the water off. I talk through the story quick now, but in the moment, I was, like, 22 years old, terrified for my life at the time. Yeah. Not knowing what was gonna go on. You were bodybuilding then? I was, yeah. In the middle of prep. I was four weeks out of the Olympia. Whoa. At this point, it was like, one of the biggest moments of feeling powerless, just completely powerless. And there's a pastor I believe in, this Richard Rohr, who talks about every man experiencing a journey of powerlessness, which leads to a sense of humility and gratitude for the rest of your life, cause you realize you're not fully in control. There's so much you can do, but there's always a level beyond what you're capable of. So I think my journey, starting with that, really LED to every moment of success. And everything that I did win, it was like, yes, I did this, but there's so much out of My control that got me here. And there's so much out of my control that could take me from here. So it kept me with a sense of humility.

title: world mental health day ü§ç sending you love.
description: world mental health day ü§ç sending you love.
transcript_text: So yesterday was World Mental Health Day, and as someone who struggles with extreme mental health issues, I have recently got myself out of a very low and dark period of my life. And if you are currently going through something or you are facing mental health issues, I kind of want to just talk about how to become stronger in yourself and how to get help if you are currently struggling. So the first thing I wanna say is reach out to someone. Never just bottle up your emotions inside. Sometimes we are weak as humans and we need connection. We need to talk to people. If you don't have family or friends that you can trust or truly rely on without feeling judged or criticized, then please seek help through professionals, whether that be a therapist or maybe it's a online call center that you can just call and speak to. But I would really recommend just please reaching out to someone that you can trust. The next thing that I want to talk about is the importance of taking care of yourself through habits. So one thing that I really noticed when my mental health would decline is if I'm going through a low period in life, we will consume ourselves with things that distract us from feeling that pain. So it will be escaping through external things, whether that is social media, TV, maybe it's different kinds of addictions. So when you realize that you're doing Things to escape that emotion. You have to feel your emotions and feel your pain and go through it and become stronger through better habits, like waking up early, going to sleep on time, going to the gym, going for a walk. Maybe it's picking up a side hustle and trying to figure out your purpose in this life. And I think that's also a very important thing, is purpose. And you have to remember that we are all created differently. We are all so unique. And the creator of the world has put you here for a reason, for a purpose. And sometimes we have to find our purpose. And that means being alone with our thoughts and not constantly consuming ourselves with things. So whether that is locking your apps, deleting apps off of your phone, um, trying to occupy yourself in better habits, but taking care of ourselves is probably one of the most important things. After being able to reach out to someone for help. And I am sending every single person who struggles with mental health so much love, because it is such a. It's such a dark journey sometimes, and you have to just find the light and truly believe that you are here for a reason, and you have so much purpose in this life.

title: Why I cut out music‚Ä¶  I think we can all agree that music is a form o...
description: Why I cut out music‚Ä¶  I think we can all agree that music is a form of art, it‚Äôs beautiful and I will always appreciate it. Although it is damaging to our soul.   I used to be addicted to music. I would wake up with it, sleep with it - when I was sad, I listened to music to make me even more sad. Vise versa when it came to ‚Äúwanting to feel happy‚Äù .  Why do we let something like music have so much control over our moods? Why is it that a song comes on when we‚Äôre training and it makes us train even harder? Or if a song we don‚Äôt like starts playing, we won‚Äôt train as hard. Let‚Äôs not forget that some of us would SKIP the gym because we forgot our headphones (I was guilty of this).  I didn‚Äôt want anything having that much control over me or my mood.  I can focus on mind to muscle connection better when I have no music. I can focus on using my mind to get me through the toughest sets of my workout / runs without depending on anything. Thus building more mental strength within me to apply to the real world.  The last thing I want to say is this is purely from a psychological view. if I were to speak about it from a faith pov - secular music is damaging and degrading to society & women. Hence why it is spiritually toxic when it comes to practicing our faith. Because we rely on music to lift us up rather than relying on the words of god. ü§ç

And I think that I am so afraid of giving my input because I am afraid of fearing what people will think. Maybe it's brands, my community. And I am now just still living this misalignment and this deep feeling of, I need to come on here and speak my truth. I wanna come on here and give my insight or my opinions on topics that might be beneficial in this world today. And so I think that I am making this video to be clear that I will still be posting fitness, food, and content that I built my platform off of. But I will now be sharing my opinions on world issues, on politics, on things that you may not care about or things that you might agree or Maybe you disagree with, but I want to just be myself fully. And whoever loves me for me is going to stay, and whoever doesn't agree with me, then is going to leave. And I think that whenever you are transitioning and your life and you're evolving as a person, you can't be afraid to lose people, you can't be afraid to take risk. And that's what it means to authentically be yourself 100% is not fearing the consequence, not fearing the risk of fully showing up as yourself. And so I am making this video to just be clear that I will be speaking about topics that might be slightly controversial, but I will still be posting fitness and food and all these other things. And I deeply appreciate every single person who has stuck by my side through this journey, because I would not be able to continue to do what I do without the support of you. And so thank you so much. And yeah, I hope that you guys enjoy the content that I share. And I love you all so much.

title: 5 things I wish I knew on my fitness journey <3  train with me for 1 ...
description: 5 things I wish I knew on my fitness journey <3  train with me for 1 month free @ upliftyou & üîó in bio to join! #1 Don't overlook the importance of nutrition and recovery #2 Follow a training program #3 discipline > motivation #4 progress isn't linear - love your journey at all phases #5 fitness will change your life, if you want to join me in the "blueprint" challenge, I will be starting it Monday August 18th. It will be taken place inside of the uplift you app. Hope these tips help you on your journey ü§ç
transcript_text: Five things I wish I knew when I first started training. So the first thing is to not overlook the importance of nutrition and recovery. So when we are training in the gym and we are pushing past our limits, training till failure, going for that last rep, we are literally breaking our muscles and tearing them apart. So we have to recover them properly by eating enough protein, getting it, enough sleep, drinking enough water. Otherwise, how do you expect your muscles to recover and help you build the dream physique that you were working towards? Which leads me into my second point, following a consistent training program. So when you follow a consistent program, you are gonna be able to master your form and then increase in weight over time. And doing movements that are your basic fundamentals, not switching it up every single time and doing random different exercises. It. It's about doing the boring things consistently in order to see results. Which leads me into my third point, discipline over motivation. Because training requires consistency, and consistency requires discipline. So when you don't feel like going to the gym, you have to remember that you are doing this to be consistent. Stop telling yourself, tomorrow, if you said you're gonna train three times a week, train three times a week. Don't go back on your word and negotiate with yourself. And now getting into number four. Progress isn't linear, and it never will be. It's gonna Be an up and down journey, and you have to accept that and embrace every single chapter of your life. Because our bodies are gonna go through so many phases. And I hear way too many people saying that I hate myself, so that's why I'm going to the gym. No, you should start loving yourself and that's why you are going to the gym or moving your body. Because when you start to associate hatred with movement, then you're not gonna be able to love this journey. Fitness has truly changed my life, not only physically, but also mentally. It has help me gain more confidence in myself, more strength. And so if you are serious about changing your life and wanting to start this journey, on Monday, August 18th, I will be doing a 30 day challenge called The Blueprint, where we practice habits that will help us stay accountable. And so I will leave more details in the caption below. I'm wishing you the best of luck with your fitness journey.

title: Recipe below üçû  this is my mama‚Äôs banana bread so it‚Äôs extra special ...
description: Recipe below üçû  this is my mama‚Äôs banana bread so it‚Äôs extra special <3  Ft. @Bloom Nutrition prebiotic soda  Ingredients:  2 cups flour 1 teaspoon baking powder ¬Ω teaspoon baking soda ¬Ω teaspoon salt ¬Ω cup (1 stick) unsalted butter, softened 1 cup sugar 2 eggs, at room temperature 1 teaspoon vanilla extract 3 medium-large very ripe bananas (1 cup mashed) ¬Ω cup sour cream or yogurt  Step 1 : Heat the oven to 325¬∞. Line a 5- by 9-inch loaf pan, preferably one with a light interior, with enough waxed paper to drape over the long sides. This will make the baked bread a cinch to remove and the pan easy to clean. Set the pan aside. Step 2 sift together the flour, baking powder, baking soda, and salt into a medium bowl. In a large bowl, cream the butter using an electric mixer. Gradually add the sugar, scraping down the sides of the bowl as necessary. Add the eggs one at a time, beating well after each addition. Next, add the vanilla extract and blend briefly. Set both bowls aside. Step 3: Peel the bananas and place them in a separate bowl. Mash them with a fork or a potato masher and measure out 1 cup. Add the sour cream and stir to blend. Set the bowl aside. Step 4: Using a wooden spoon (see box at right), blend a third of the dry mixture into the butter-sugar mixture. Add the rest of the ingredients in this order, stirring well after each addition: half of the banana mixture, half of the remaining dry mixture, the rest of the banana mix-ture, the rest of the dry mixture. Next, add mix-ins if desired  Step 5: Scrape the batter into the prepared pan and smooth the top with a spoon. Bake on the center oven rack until a tester inserted deep into the center of the bread comes out clean, about 70 to 75 minutes. Step 6 Transfer the bread to a cooling rack and cool it in the pan for about 20 minutes. Using the waxed paper, lift the bread from the pan and place it on the rack. Pull down the sides of the paper and allow the bread to cool thoroughly before slicing. Makes 10 or more servings  #bloompartner

title: Some men ** - this is why we need more only women gyms
description: Some men ** - this is why we need more only women gyms
transcript_text: I want to talk about gym attire and the fact that men are literally going on this app and bashing women for what they wear in the gym. And they are saying things that women are going to the gym with the intention to be sexualized and the intention to always have men's attention on them and wanting men to look at them in a lustful way. And not only are they talking about gym attire, but they are also talking about things that women wear to the beach. And I am someone who wears a hijab, but I was also a woman who once wore shorts and sports bras to the gym. So I understand both perspectives. Whenever I used to wear shorts and sports bras, I wanted to feel confident within myself. I like going to the gym and feeling comfortable in the clothes that I'm wearing, and I love looking at myself in the mirror and being able to see my pump. If I ever had a man staring at me, I would always stare him down back as if like, why are you staring at me? I am here to train. Doesn't matter what I'm wearing. I don't give you the right to stare at me. And you know what's so crazy? Men feel very entitled. If we dress a certain way, meaning if we are maybe not as covered, that means it has, like, they have the right to be able to stare us down. Like, no, you need to learn self control, learn how to literally lower your gaze. Like, women are not asking for your attention, and this is not a job at all, men. But they will come on here and criticize women for wearing shorts and sports bras, but then they will come on here and criticize women who are fully covered up. So, you know what? Please let women wear what they want to wear. And if you ever want to give education onto why women should be modest, talk about it in a way where it's Protection from men living in a hypersexualized world, which is one of the reasons why I cover, because I was tired of getting catcalled and constantly looked up and down because men treat us as if we are objects. And so, again, not a bash at men. And for the women that are applauding the men for speaking about us in a negative way or speaking about the women wearing shorts and sports bras to the gym, you need to really, like, look within. Like, what's empowering as women? Uplifting each other, not putting each other down by saying one person is better than the other. And yeah, um, why am I getting emotional about this topic? Like, literally, again, it's not a job at men, but, like, seriously, y'all need a reality check to look within yourselves and learn how to have more self control by lowering your gaze.

title: At home full body workout // workout details on insta ü§ç
description: At home full body workout // workout details on insta ü§ç
transcript_text: All you need is 45 minutes to do this at home. Full body workout. And we're doing a circuit, so it's basically all back to back. And the first movement we are doing is a B stance RDL with a row. And so for your stance, you wanna have one foot in front of the other, the back foot being toe down, heel up. A B stance RDL is one of my favourite movements for growing the glutes and adding in a single arm row is great for your back. The second movement is a DB sumo squat. So you're basically gonna have a bit of a wide stance and you're gonna lean forward, pushing your hips back as you come down for a squat. The third movement is a DB half get up. This is going to target our core, and I'm basically holding my stomach to make sure that I'm really engaging my core. Make sure you repeat the same amount of reps on each side. The fourth movement we are doing is a side lunge with a knee drive. This is one of my favourite movements for stability and balance, but also growing our lower body. And the final movement we are doing is a bicep curl into a press. This is going to target our biceps and our shoulders. I hope you enjoy this workout and let me know if you try it.

title: don‚Äôt be afraid of moving ü§ç
description: don‚Äôt be afraid of moving ü§ç
transcript_text: I moved all alone from Dallas to New York City and it's been three months so here are some things that I've Learned the first thing is moving out of your hometown seems scary cause you're leaving family friends and stepping into a new chapter where everything is unfamiliar will seem scary but I promise you the these are the moments that are truly going to build you and I always live by the quote discomfort is where growth occurs another thing that I Learned because I know that I made the right decision was not listening to people around you so it could be family friends that are telling you not to go to a different city they are unintentionally holding you back thinking that they know what is best for you but in reality don't and say you make a mistake it's okay to fail and you have to allow yourself to experience life and go through the times where you learn and maybe you did make a wrong decision but you won't know until you do it and the last thing is learn how to be okay with being alone because when you are in a city where you don't really know anyone it might feel like you're lonely but you're not because if you learn how to love your own company and you invest your time back into the habits that keep you fulfilled in life you will be so strong in this journey of moving to a new city

title: what I eat in a day ft. @Bloom Nutrition #bloompartner

transcript_text: As someone who loves food but also loves fitness, here is everything that I eat. So I start off my morning with matcha because I cut out coffee a year ago. I drink this while I read and write and work and then I get into my breakfast which is high in protein. Steak, bacon, eggs. I also mix my water with creatine and greens for muscle recovery. And then this meal was honestly so good. So simple. I literally finished every single inch of it. I prioritise lots of water and then I also have another matcha cause it's just so good. Before I got into my workout I had a quick snack which was dates and almond butter which is high in fibre. I also had an energy drink. Well half of it because it spilled over and then got into an at home session. And then after that I had my lunch. I literally just had potatoes, chicken and salad. But yeah, that was everything I ate.

transcript_text: If you want to be consistent, you have to spend your weekends preparing. I say this because every single time I don't spend a weekend preparing properly, my week is not the same. So let's start with, if you are not consistent in the gym or running, whatever it is that you enjoy doing, start by just stretching. And after that, make a plan. Know exactly what you're gonna be doing throughout the week. Don't wait till the last minute. And then what are you eating? Because if you are not fueling your body properly, you are gonna feel low energy, and then you're gonna also choose unhealthy options. So I highly recommend you prepare in advance, whether that's meal prepping, choosing healthy options, but know exactly what you're eating and what time of the day that you're eating. Another crucial step is being able to offset your mind. So going out alone, and I say this because it's so important for us as creatives, and every single one of us has creativity, but you're able to spend time, see what you love to do, like, who are you as a person? And all of these things are gonna help you prepare for the week and have a strong mind.

transcript_text: Before I put on the hijab, I used to crave so much external validation. And by that, I meant I loved being the baddest in the room, okay? I loved feeling, like, walking in and everyone looks at me like, as arrogant as that sounds, that's the person I was. And honestly, what LED me to putting on the hijab was not only connecting to my faith, but it was really understanding the meaning of modesty. I craved external validation so much to the point where it literally was my confidence. That's where I got my confidence was by walking into a room and someone looking at me or someone telling me that I was beautiful based off of my external. So there's many reasons for modesty. My reason was, yes, protecting my beauty, yes, getting closer to god, but also to not crave external validation anymore and feel confident from within me. And so something I realized now is even though I put on the hijab, you're still gonna crave it. But now you just have to still find that confidence from within you. Always.

title: For all the aspiring influencers who practice faith, always stay firm...
description: For all the aspiring influencers who practice faith, always stay firm in your truth ‚ú®
transcript_text: I got tagged in a video of a guy talking about how he wanted to become a fitness influencer, but he wanted to practice faith and not show his body because of modesty. And he was of the Christian faith. Now, he was saying this because he wanted to be able to basically gain an audience off of respecting him and being able to trust his opinion in fitness because of how he built his physique. And so this is a valid perspective, because for someone who has built their platform off of showing their body and then putting on the hijab, it has been a constant question that I get of does she still have the same physique? Or we don't feel as inspired anymore because you're not showing your body. And I think the issue with this is, as I've evolved, my perspective in life, fitness is much more than just going to the gym for your body. And if you maintain that same mindset that I am just going to train or I'm just going to for a run because I wanna lose weight, you are not gonna be able to maintain consistency because that's such a short term goal. You should have the mindset that I am doing this for my overall health, and there are so many people in this world that have that mindset. So for you not posting your content because you are scared of faith, right? You're scared of not being able To practice your faith in full. If you do post content, don't start conforming to societal beliefs and expectations. Start staying true to you and find that community and that audience that truly resonate with your message. And I promise you will gain way more success, even long term, because you are staying true to your beliefs and that is always going to win in the long run.

Journaling by writing out what you‚Äôre grateful for & also reflecting on your actions and taking accountability  2. taking care of your appearance / dressing to please yourself and God (not others)  3. Taking care of your health in every way, our body is a gift from God so we should treat it like one ü§ç also drinking @Bloom Nutrition #bloompartner greens to get in my greens intake ü•¨  4. Practicing and truly understanding Gods teachings so you can apply it to your life.  5. Be kind to yourself, learn who God is. transcript_text: As someone who put on the hijab two years ago, I still struggle with faith sometimes. So here are some things that get me closer to god. The first thing is journaling. You can do this after prayer. You can do it every morning or at night. And just writing the things that you're grateful for in life. And also holding yourself accountable for all your actions. The second thing is taking care of yourself by presenting yourself in a certain way and not only for others, but for yourself and the sake of god. The third thing is your nutrition. The foods that you put into your body are going to impact your energy and the way that you feel. Not only that, showing appreciation and love and care to those around you. Once you're taking care of yourself, you then need to focus on building your relationship with god through his teachings. Whether that's learning and reading and writing, or maybe it's prayer and trying to be more present in the moment. And the last thing I wanna mention is faith is a journey and you have to take it one step at a time. Sometimes it will feel weaker and sometimes it will feel stronger. But never lose trust and hope in god.

title: Stop sleeping like this #gym #fitness #workout #bodybuilding

transcript_text: I was told to never sleep like this because I lift weights. And now I understand why. A few years ago, my friend had to get shoulder surgery three times. When he asked the surgeon why this kept happening, the doctor told him something quite crazy. Sleeping on your stomach with your arm bent overhead puts hours of pressure on your shoulder joints, especially if you lift weights. At first I thought this was a stretch, but this position compresses your rotator cuff and bursa. And if your shoulders are already inflamed from training, those nightly hours of pressure only accelerate the wear. Well, I don't want to scare you. These small actions add up over the years. So try sleep with your arms at your side because it may save you some future pain.

description: Leg day incoming ‚è≥ Squat Form Check üí™üèæ As someone who‚Äôs been lifting for a few years now, I can attest to the importance of proper squat form. One of the most common mistakes I see people make is not going low enough. It‚Äôs easy to get in the habit of only squatting to parallel, but to get the most out of the exercise, you need to go deeper. Another mistake is letting your knees cave in. This can cause serious injury if left unchecked. To fix this, focus on pushing your knees out as you squat üèãüèæ‚Äç‚ôÄÔ∏è  Finally, make sure your back stays straight throughout the movement. If you start to round your back, you‚Äôre putting unnecessary strain on your spine. Keep these tips in mind, and you‚Äôll be on your way to perfect squat form. title: From everything I‚Äôve seen happening in my second home LA I felt it wa...
description: From everything I‚Äôve seen happening in my second home LA I felt it was only right to share my story on immigration. Sure I can stay silent to make others comfortable but my job ain‚Äôt to make you feel comfortable or be relatable it‚Äôs to speak my truth and my story. When you‚Äôre born in privilege you often times forget to be empathetic to those who haven‚Äôt had the same upbringing or luck as you. My parents risked a lot to make my future bright for me. You see, for me, moving to a new place gave me opportunities I would of never ever had in my hometown. Have empathy, be compassionate and remember it‚Äôs SO easy to judge.
transcript_text: I admit a lot of people are right when they say I work too much. But there is a reason. It all started when I was 5 years old. My Albanian parents decided to immigrate to the UK. Making our way on a tiny boat as a refugee and in the back of a banana truck. Don't even ask me why it was a banana truck. I still remember feeling cold and confused in the back of the truck, wondering what adventure we were gonna go. Little did I know my life would never look the same. But naivety is bliss. Like most, my parents grew up not having a lot. My mom and dad work three jobs and oftentimes I'd school and even go and help my mum clean offices after hours. I grew up with my mum saying Christiana, you better be the hardest working person in the room. Ever since then, kinda stuck to me. Being a 1st gen comes with a lot of responsibility. From grinding to get my law degree in university whilst working as a waitress, to starting my first brand on my university laptop I bought with my student loan. The bottom line is I fundamentally wanna make my mum and dad proud. I grew up no business, there's no mentor, no financial experts around me. Often times I'm pretty scared to lose it all. And I admit that the overworking is simply a response to my trauma. To help me Handle the fear of losing everything I've worked for and going back to being that five year old refugee girl in the back of a. My biggest achievement today, minus having my son, is not my businesses or the awards I've won. It's a fact that I got to retire my parents and buy them their very first home. It was a fact that my mom never has to worry and regardless of any family domestics, I'll always take care of. The responsibility often feels heavy, but you see, I have no choice as the safety that I have is the one I was never given. And I'm just simply trying to build my own.

title: Need help with hip mobility? Many claim the 90:90 rotation or shin bo...
description: Need help with hip mobility? Many claim the 90:90 rotation or shin box is the best BUT I find this is too advanced for a lot of people. The hip airplane is a better more simple option - but always follow it was a stability drill for best results!  . Shout out @Muscle and Motion for the amazing anatomy graphics!
transcript_text: Need more hip mobility. The 90 90 rotation or shin box is an advanced exercise that unfortunately many can't do without compensations or pain, especially if they have really limited hip internal rotation. A more beginner friendly hip mobility drill is called the hip airplane. Set up like you're going to do a single leg Ardell, then twist your pelvis down until you feel a stretch in your lateral glutes. Hold for a few seconds before coming up. Follow this mobility drill with an exercise like the side plank clamshell. Held for five seconds to stabilize the hip joint. Notice the improvements in mobility after this sequence, which then allowed her to move much further in the 90 90 rotation. Now completely pain free. Oh yeah, definitely feels better.

title: Have back pain when lifting? @Jaz & Ange
description: Have back pain when lifting? @Jaz & Ange
transcript_text: Hey, how's your girl, man? Uh, she left me. Oh. But I got the van. It's nice. Stephanie had been dealing with back pain for months that limited her ability to squat and even lift this 135 pounds without symptoms. During my assessment with the single leg bridge test, she could feel her glutes firing really hard on her left side. But when she went to the right side, no glutes, just quads, hamstrings, and her groin muscles working hard. This meant she was dealing with gluteal amnesia, a phenomenon by which pain corrupts the body's signaling process, creating problems in timing, coordination, and intensity of muscle contraction for her, leading to problems in hip extension. So part of her back pain recovery required us to focus on the glutes and get them to fire better. We started with a double leg bridge with a band around the knees and paired this with the McGill big three core stability routine of 10 second holds. She then slowly rebuilt her lifts and was able to get back to lifting heavy weights again pain free.

title: Overhead press to build shoulders? Don‚Äôt miss this mobility! @Davidjb...

transcript_text: I'm gonna show you the difference between what I do for shoulder press and what y'all think I should do for shoulder press. In the comments, I see it a lot. You're not going all the way up and locking out your elbows. I stop about right here just so I could, like, feel that. That my muscle neck. title: Before modern dumbbells and barbell chest press, there was the Persia...
description: Before modern dumbbells and barbell chest press, there was the Persian Sang (Stone) Shield. The grip, rotation and stability challenge of balancing the shields throughout the press is quite a unique strength challenge. Here Kelly is performing the traditional press (though there are a number of different variations)  Sang is one of the 4 traditional training tools used , along with calisthenics, in the ancient Persian/Iranian martial art known as Zurkhaneh Sport and is one of the world‚Äôs first strength training systems.  Large flat wooden shields, the sang (meaning ‚Äústone‚Äù in Persian) mimics the weight and form of battlefield shields once used by Persian warriors. Typically weighing between 15 to 60 kilograms, the sang shields are an integral part of Zurkhaneh training, combining physical strength with spiritual discipline and cultural heritage. The other 3 pieces of equipment used are the Shena board (a wooden board to perform push-ups on), Persian Meel/Mil (a style of wooden club) and Kabbadeh (steel bow)  Video: @kellsbells88/IG Sang Shield made by Saeed @northernclubcraft #ancientsports #persianmeels #physicalculture #zurkhaneh

transcript_text: What is the point of this plate? Why the hell am I squatting with my heels on a plate? Here's why Sam Sulek and other lifters squat with their heels on plates or with the weightlifting shoe. The most simple answer is that it changes technique. When you squat with your heels elevated, it allows more knee over toe translation so that you can squat deeper with a more upright chest compared to without elevation. Ankle mobility levels will dictate how much knee over toe motion you get and the angle at which your trunk assumes to stay balanced. Have less ankle mobility and you lean forward more. Doing so then shifts more of that load demand onto the hips. Whereas if you are more upright by elevating your heels, that load is more evenly distributed amongst hips and knees, and some people feel like it activates their quads a little bit more.

title: One of the hardest things in life is choosing to be uncomfortable and...
description: One of the hardest things in life is choosing to be uncomfortable and adopt a new identity‚Äî to lace up your shoes, step outside, and run toward the version of you that doesn't exist yet. Running isn't just physical. It's a mirror. And in the beginning? It humbles you. Your body resists, your mind negotiates, and everything in you wants to quit. Why? Because the comfort zone is seductive ‚Äî it convinces you that change is too hard, that growth is too far, that you're not made for it. Staying consistent is the basis of the success behind every journey. The struggle becomes strength. The pain becomes purpose. The steps that once felt impossible start to feel like home. And that's where the magic happens...when discomfort becomes your new normal and movement becomes your medicine. I will be honest if I didn't have to negotiate with myself a thousand times before I relinquished to the idea that if I want to run a marathon, I'm going to temporarily lose the identity l've had for so many years. I like being strong, BUT THIS IS A DIFFERENT KIND OF STRONG. And so many people don't even get to experience the other side of why running is so freeing. So here we go, stay resilient. You are your biggest priority! Give it time. Trust the process. Let the hard things make you better.  #running #marathontraining #childofgod #motivation #fitnessmotivation #mondaymotivation #longrun #cardio
transcript_text: Doing hard things is what's going to keep you resilient. Mile two, mile three. Let's go. Mile 4, mile five, mile Six Mile seven. Who told me to run in this heat? But mile 8, Mile 9. You are your biggest priority, your biggest investment. Show up. You don't have to compete with anyone else. You're doing this for you. Mile 10, baby.

title: Share this with someone who needs it! If you've ever struggled to sta...
description: Share this with someone who needs it! If you've ever struggled to stay consistent with your workouts, the issue isn't willpower. It's how your brain is wired to form habits. Habits are built through a loop: cue, routine, reward.When you repeat a behavior, your brain releases dopamine. Dopamine is a neurotransmitter that reinforces the action and encourages you to do it again. Over time, that behavior shifts from conscious effort to automatic pattern. This happens in the basal ganglia, the part of your brain responsible for habit formation and motor control. The more consistent you are, the less effort it takes to show up. YOUR HOMEWORK: 1. ÔªøÔªøÔªøPair your workout with a daily cue (like morning coffee or finishing work). 2. ÔªøÔªøÔªøSet up your environment to make movement the easy choice. 3. ÔªøÔªøÔªøLower the barrier by committing to just five minutes. 4. ÔªøÔªøÔªøAnd don't skip the reward, celebrate completion, because positive emotion strengthens the neural connection. This is how real behavior change happens.  Not overnight, but through intentional repetition that rewires your brain to crave the thing that once felt hard. Consistency creates identity. Identity sustains action. You become what you repeatedly do. #childofgod #hijadecristo #motivation #mondaymotivation #inspiration #realtalk #consistency

So your brain sees a trigger and follows it with a behavior like training and locks it in with a reward. That post workout high that you feel, that's dopamine. That's your brain saying, let's do that again. And this happens in a part of the brain called the basal ganglia. It's where repeated movement becomes automatic. That's why workouts get easier to start once you have made them part of your identity. So here's what actually works. I want you to take notes, stack your workout to an existing habit. For example, after you make your morning coffee, change into your workout clothes, then use visual cues. title: Feeling sore & unmotivated? Move anyway. Here's why: Soreness and low...
description: Feeling sore & unmotivated? Move anyway. Here's why: Soreness and low motivation the day or a couple of days after a tough workout is normal. While it's counterintuitive to think of training or moving, it doesn't mean you should skip movement entirely. In fact, it's movement that often gets you out of the funk. I always emphasize that movement creates movement. When you start with just 5-10 minutes of low-intensity Zone 2 cardio (like walking, cycling, or light elliptical), or even a simple dynamic warm-up (think hip openers, bodyweight squats, shoulder circles like in this video), you're doing more than just loosening up your body. You're activating your brain and nervous system too. Here's what's happening: - Your brain releases endorphins: feel-good chemicals that relieve pain and elevate mood. - You stimulate dopamine: a neurotransmitter tied to motivation and reward. - Blood flow increases to your muscles and prefrontal cortex, helping you feel more alert, focused, and ready to train. - Your parasympathetic nervous system starts to calm inflammation and muscle tension as your body adapts. The first few minutes might feel stiff or slow, but stay with it. Once you warm up, the resistance fades. You're not being lazy, you're just HUMAN! . Start small, let momentum take over and watch how you will feel amazing. PS: I even did pull ups today and had the greatest workout which means tomorrow I'll hop back on and do some zone two cardio and some major stretching. My warm up: 1x8 reps - Neck circles: esch side - Arm circles - Trunk rotations - Hip circles each side - Shin box - Downdog to plank  SHARE THIS WITH A FRIEND, AND LET'S KEEP MOVING. #childofgod #hijadecristo #sculptprogram #strengthtraining #motivation #legday #mobility #stretching #fitnessmotivation #sore #inspiration #athomeworkout
transcript_text: Tribe, have you ever been so sore that everything in you wanted to skip your next workout? If that's you, keep watching. Now, let's break down some science for you. If you want to recover and get motivated for that next workout, you must move. Just five to 10 minutes of light Zone 2 cardio will increase circulation, reduce muscle stiffness, and deliver oxygen and nutrients to sore muscles. Your brain releases endorphins, your natural painkillers, and dopamine, which boosts motivation. You're also activating your prefrontal cortex, improving your focus and mood. So the next time you feel too sore to move and unmotivated, just a few minutes of movement, your whole system will shift, and you'll be ready for your next session.

description: SOUNDüîä Resilient bodies for years to come, ladies save this one and share it with your girlfriends. Scoop low, feel the stretch, keep it fluid. ‚ö´Ô∏èSingle leg calf raises ‚Äî this builds strength and balance right where you push off in every stride. title: READ BELOW TRIBE! TAG SOMEONE WHO NEEDS THIS: Pain is not the enemy-i...
description: READ BELOW TRIBE! TAG SOMEONE WHO NEEDS THIS: Pain is not the enemy-it's the body's built-in intelligence speaking to you. We live in a time where there's a pill for everything‚Äî instant relief, quick fixes, numb the discomfort. But if we never allow ourselves to feel, how do we ever evolve? We've been conditioned to see pain as something to avoid, to silence, to numb. But in reality, pain is a powerful protective mechanism. It's your body's way of saying: "Pay attention." Pain signals are designed to help you adapt and overcome. When you touch something hot, your nerves fire off a warning, making you pull away before real damage is done. When you push too hard in training, soreness tells you where to recover and rebuild. When you experience emotional pain, it forces you to reflect, adjust, and move differently. But what happens when we constantly mask pain instead of addressing it? We weaken our ability to adapt. We suppress the lesson. We disconnect from our natural ability to heal. Instead of running from pain, lean in and listen. Your body is always guiding you toward a solution-whether it's movement, nourishment, rest, or a mindset shift. True strength isn't found in avoidance; it's built in the moments when you choose to face it, feel it, and evolve through it. Your pain is not your weakness. It's your wisdom. #childofgod #hijadecristo #BuiltToAdapt #motivation #inspiration #workoutmotivation #fitnessmotivation
transcript_text: Pain is temporary. It may last for a minute or an hour or a day or even a year. But eventually it will subside and something else will take its place. If I quit, however, it will last forever.

title: Simple adjustments make all the difference in how you feel these exer...
description: Simple adjustments make all the difference in how you feel these exercises. Here's a breakdown of how to get the most from them. Forearm plank - push away from floor with your forearms and tuck the hips under at the same time. This activates the core muscles and the lats. Keep your entire lower body engaged with knees extended. Modified side plank - similar cues as before but also lift your hips away from the floor to activate the obliques. Feet can be stacked or top foot in front like I'm showing here. Keep neck elongated. Reverse plank - lift those hips by driving the heels into the floor, activating your glutes and hamstrings. Push away from the foam roller to avoid any excess pressure on the wrists. Think of creating a long straight line from the top of your head to your feet. Try these tips and let me know how you feel afterwards! It's all about how you train, not just going through the motions. Use that mind muscle connection to feel the difference. title: Have you ever watched kids grow and play? Unless the parental figure ...
description: Have you ever watched kids grow and play? Unless the parental figure creates a behavioral pattern of fear around that child, he or she is fearless and unstoppable. Where does the fear come into play? Interestingly enough, when we stop playing and moving like we used to. Then what happens when we get older in this modern world?‚ÄîWE STOP MOVING. We get in our chairs to learn, in our cars to drive, our social events to entertain and most of us become parents with big responsibilities. Then, the pattern changes to working out and moving because you have to in order to lose weight. Exercise becomes a chore instead of a daily practice, our lives become limited to the resources we have to find movement with anything and everywhere. The limitations you feel today are often created by a lack of movement in those patterns. Often you feed into that reality because it sounds easier to deal and adapt to the thought of getting older and accepting the pain you're in instead of working towards reversing it all (more o often than not this is doable, preventable, and sustainable). I wanted to make this post to give you not only a little fun thing to do and practice when you're bored and want to try to master something new, but to open your mind that it will be hard to start to move again, but the body will adapt in the same way that it adapted to you not doing SO. description: I wanted to share what l've been doing lately in the mornings when I wake up super stiff, all of these moments are from my new mobility program Sculpt üëâüèΩwww.tru.training  The less mobile we become, the more in pain and prone to injury we will be. title: Over 10 years ago I had this conversation with myself and it changed ...
description: Over 10 years ago I had this conversation with myself and it changed everything for me. I had the choice of staying in pain or getting myself out of that space with the resources I had. I experienced first hand how my mind was the most powerful tool to shift my mindset and my perceived reality. What you think you start becoming as those thoughts manifest into action. We often see our goals as so far away that we tell ourselves they are impossible to reach. We create this narrative that we aren't good enough, courageous enough, and often not deserving enough. The truth is that the longer we wait in "the pain" we find ourselves in, the harder it will be to come out of it. Nothing ever happens sustainably out of drastic change - long-term successful changes occur out of small habits and practices we take on a daily basis. Forget about how long, how far, or how much it will take you and START working right now with what you have. The growing pains you feel today will be the foundation for the resilience you need to be as successful as you need to be. Monday's are meant to be crushed. I love you my tribe! #childofgod #motivationmonday #mentalhealth #healthymindset
transcript_text: Would you rather go through the growing pains and be at point B? Or would you rather just stay there in pain, feeling bad about yourself, constantly complaining out loud with yourself about the things that you have to change? Something has to change, and that is you, how you think about things. And you have to get on the other side. It's going to be hard, but that is the process. You're there, learning, and that's how you build mental grit. Every single day that you do something that you didn't wanna do, you get stronger, stronger, stronger, stronger. Until you get to a point where you have defined who you are, where you wanna be, and you stop complaining.

transcript_text: When you become a gym influencer or you become an influencer in the fitness space or you start posting content, naturally you want your videos to get more views. You wanna track more followers and you wanna, you know, build an audience. However, a lot of influencers and gym influencers won't tell you that the thing that gets the more views is doing close UPS on assets that you know are inappropriate, you know, doing specific movements and zooming the camera in so that it gets more views. Doing inappropriate things you probably wouldn't post regularly unless you had followers. And the more followers you get, the more confidence you have to post that type of content. So naturally, as I started gaining more views and having more of an audience, I realized I was attracting the wrong audience and I wanted to change that. I'm also going into a field that's very professional. I just took the bar exam. I want to become an attorney and I'm very well close to that. So I took down a lot of my videos. I, you know, removed so many things. And with that, that also meant that I was losing views because I was no longer posting that inappropriate content that was getting me so many views. I want my page to be about motivation, discipline, grit, getting to where you wanna be because I worked hard to get the body that I have, but also to get to where I Am today from going from Hamilton Ontario to Miami, Florida. It's a big shift. Now what that means that a lot of brands will no longer support you because you don't have those views. A lot of right brands won't want to work with you because you don't have those views and I realized that I was okay with that. However, there was one brand that always always committed to continue working with me despite my view count going down because I no longer post those types of videos and that was YSL YSL, I love you because you continue to send me PR even though I don't post specific content that used to get the views it it it would and um, yeah, they sent me this how adorable they sent me the new Black Opium perfume they sent me their new blush which just look at how freaking cute this packaging is and they sent me a new lip gloss and mind you, they could they've continued sending me things like how adorable it's literally red themed. transcript_text: I'm done with fake videos. I want you guys to see what real discipline looks like. This summer I'm gonna be graduating from law school and start studying for the bar exam. And I want you guys to come along my journey and see how I'm staying consistent in the gym, eating healthy while having a 9 to 5 study schedule for the next three or so months. I saw posting content on TikTok because all of my content was no longer about being provocative. When you're not pushing out that kind of content, less people are clicking on your videos. And I'm at a point where I just don't care. I want my audience to see what discipline is. I want to show you guys that even though you're studying all the time or you're working, you can still stay committed to your goals. Even though I'm a content creator myself, I found myself comparing myself to content creators that had no affiliation or relation to me. These are people that don't have full time jobs, aren't in school full time. They're have more resources than the next person would. And show you guys how I'm studying, what I'm doing, what my bad days look like, how I'm staying committed to my health and fitness. And I hope you guys get something from it.

title: Sorry bro üò¢ 3 signs you‚Äôll never achieve your dream physique‚Ä¶
description: Sorry bro üò¢ 3 signs you‚Äôll never achieve your dream physique‚Ä¶
transcript_text: Here are three signs that you'll never achieve your dream physique. Sorry. I've spent 14 years building my body and I've worked with over 1,000 clients at this point, both in person and online. And the first sign that somebody isn't going to make it in the long run is not having a clear why. If you don't have a strong why, you will not have the grit to endure the inevitable discomfort that comes along with shifting lifestyle habits, hitting the workouts you don't wanna hit, and resisting the impulses and old patterns that have kept you stuck. Which leads me to my second sign, and that's being hyper fixated on quick results. Now, wanting to optimize your results is not a bad thing. But if somebody's number one concern is getting from point A to point B as quickly as possible, usually these are the people who are going extreme or not at all, so nothing sticks. Still in the mindset that fitness is temporary instead of a lifestyle that they live. And finally, the surest sign that somebody will never achieve their dream physique is they think they know everything. These are the people who are unwilling to learn or adjust their approach. They have set the limit on their potential because they think they have it all figured out. And if you did, by the way, you'd probably be well on your way to achieving your dream physique, or you'd already have it.

title: Struggling to grow your quads? Try this tweak üî• DM me ‚Äò1ON1‚Äô on IG fo...
description: Struggling to grow your quads? Try this tweak üî• DM me ‚Äò1ON1‚Äô on IG for structured programming & personalized guidance ü§ù #legday #quadworkout #workouttips
transcript_text: Try this if you're struggling to grow your quads. Most people start leg day with a squat. And that's great, especially if you're newer to lifting or it's already working well for you. But here's the problem. Squats don't directly target the rectus femoris, that mid quad muscle, the way a leg extension does. On top of that, squats create a ton of fatigue that carries over into the rest of your workout. That's why I recommend flipping the order. Start with leg extensions before your squat movement. Since they're an isolation exercise, you'll get better quad recruitment right out of the gate with far less fatigue. Going single leg can be even better and is especially useful once you're maxing out the machine. If overall leg development is your priority, keep squats first. But if quad growth has been lagging, start your next leg day with leg extensions and see the difference for yourself.

transcript_text: Full upper body workout in under an hour. Here's why I structure it this way I start with a chest supported row to target the upper back and get pulling volume in first. Then an incline machine press since upper chest is a priority for me and I noticed less of a strength drop here compared to starting with flat. Next is a single arm lat pull down to hit the lats directly and even out strength. Side side back to chest with a flat press for overall pec development. Then lateral raises since my side delts haven't been hit effectively up to this point. And finally arms. A single arm row pushdown for triceps and a barbell curl for biceps. Both great all around movements. Seven movements under an hour. Focus on efficiency and balance across the upper body.

transcript_text: Balance is bullshit. As nice as it sounds, trying to balance everything in life equally is not realistic and it won't help you achieve anything meaningful. title: Different grips don‚Äôt hit different tricep heads ü•ê You just need 1 pu...
description: Different grips don‚Äôt hit different tricep heads ü•ê You just need 1 pushdown + 1 overhead. Don‚Äôt overcomplicate it ü§ù #tricepsworkout #armday #musclebuilding #fitnesstips #hypertrophy
transcript_text: Alright, let's clear this up real quick. The first three grips he shows trains your triceps in the same exact way. Your triceps main function is to extend the elbow. Changing your wrist positioning does not magically change which head of the tricep is working. The lateral and medial heads will be working no matter what kind of extension that you're doing. The only thing that matters is shoulder positioning for the long head of the tricep, which is the only one that crosses the shoulder joint. So when your arms are by your sides, you're training the long head in the shortened position. When your arms are overhead, you're training them in the lengthened position. You don't need four variations for triceps. You just need two movements, one with your arms by your sides, one with your arms overhead.

transcript_text: If you're still obsessing over the perfect rep range or training split, let me save you some time. Most of the best way to build muscle advice is blown way out of proportion. You don't need a specific number of reps to grow. If you're training close to failure, whether it's five reps or 30, you'll build muscle. Intensity matters more than rep range. Personally, I stick to low to moderate reps because I can hit the stimulating reps faster with less fatigue. Now how many days a week should you train? Whether it's three, four, five or six days, pick what you can actually stick to. I used to train six days a week. Now I train four to five. Sustainability wins every time. Lastly, recovery is the most underrated key to growth. You can do everything right in the gym, but if your sleep sucks, your stress is high, and you're under eating, your progress will stall.

transcript_text: This is the most common mistake I see people making on an incline press. They'll take a wide grip similar to a flat press, and they'll keep those elbows flared as they press, thinking that just because we're on an incline bench, we're going to be biasing the upper chest fibers, which isn't necessarily the case. Our middle to lower chest fibers love to have the elbows slightly more flared to bring those elbows across the body. And, yes, your upper chest is going to assist with that. But if you really want to bias the upper chest, we need more shoulder flexing. Our upper chest really helps us bring that. That elbow up and across the body. So if you want to bias the upper chest more, what you can do is bring that grip width in a little bit to be just outside of shoulder width. And this will allow you to tuck your elbows throughout the movement, bring in more shoulder flexion, which will give you better overall upper chest activation.

title: Big biceps get all the attention‚Ä¶ but triceps make up most of your ar...

To effectively train the long head, you should prioritize movements where the elbow stays fixed. ‚úÖ Arms overhead = long head in a stretched position (overhead rope extensions, French presses, skull crushers) ‚úÖ Arms by sides or behind you = long head in a more shortened position (rope push downs, cross body extensions, or kickbacks) ‚úÖ JM press or dips = solid for lateral & medial heads but won‚Äôt do much for the long head. I like to do üëâüèª 1 overhead + pushdown or kickback movement. Twice a week. That‚Äôs it. Occasionally, I‚Äôll sprinkle in dips or a JM Press. You don‚Äôt need 5 variations every week‚Äîjust smart execution üëåüèª ‚ûñ‚ûñ‚ûñ‚ûñ‚ûñ‚ûñ‚ûñ‚ûñ #tricepsworkout #armday #buildmuscle #tricepstraining #fitnesseducation #longheadtriceps #hypertrophytips #smarttraining #mensfitnesstips #musclebuilding101
transcript_text: If you want massive arms, you need to build your triceps since they make up most of them, especially the long head, which is the biggest of the three heads. The triceps main job is elbow extension, but the long head also crosses the shoulder joint, so your shoulder position matters. That's why overhead movements like French presses or cable overhead extensions stretch the long head and train it in its lengthened position. Movements like rope push downs or cross body extensions train it in a more shortened position. JM presses are great for the lateral and medial head, but similar to other pressing movements, they don't effectively train the long head. So if you want crisp croissants for triceps, I like to do one overhead movement and one with arms by my sides. These should be the priority since the long head is the thickest and these will still train the lateral and medial heads. You can sprinkle in something like a J and press if you're lacking lateral head thickness, but you shouldn't need more than one to two triceps exercises per session two times per week.

transcript_text: Most guys butcher their hamstring training. Let me clear it up for you. Your hamstrings do two main things. One, hip extension, think RDLS2. Knee flexion, think leg curls. Except for the short head of the biceps femoris, which only crosses the knee. So yes, you need both movement patterns when it comes to exercise selection. Do seated leg curls if you can. They lock you in hip flexion, so you're training the hamstrings in a stretch position, which is great for growth. If you don't have one lying, leg curls work too. For hip extension, go with the stiff leg deadlifts or 45 degree hip hinges. The key is keeping the knee relatively fixed while the hips move. Here's what not to do leg presses for hamstrings. They combine knee flexion and hip extension, meaning the length of the hamstrings stay the same, so you don't get a good stretch or contraction. In other words, no real stimulus. If you're serious about growing your hamstrings, don't neglect your leg curls and hip hinges.

title: Slow eccentrics don‚Äôt build more muscle ‚Äî and they may actually hinde...
description: Slow eccentrics don‚Äôt build more muscle ‚Äî and they may actually hinder hypertrophy if overemphasized. Research shows muscle activation is significantly lower during the eccentric phase than the concentric phase. While some eccentric control is important for technique and injury prevention, excessively slow eccentrics can reduce total training volume by forcing you to use lighter loads. Why does that matter? Mechanical tension ‚Äî the key driver of hypertrophy ‚Äî is compromised when you sacrifice load or concentric effort just to slow the lowering phase. That doesn‚Äôt mean you should neglect the eccentric altogether. Controlled eccentrics matter ‚Äî just not prolonged eccentrics. Your best bet? Lower the weight under control (1-2 seconds is plenty), then focus on producing maximum force during the concentric phase ‚Äî where most muscle-building stimulus occurs. Don‚Äôt waste energy on tempo for tempo‚Äôs sake. Use eccentrics to reinforce solid technique ‚Äî not to slow your gains. #hypertrophytraining #musclebuildingtips #musclegrowth #transformationcoach #gains #muscle #workouttips

transcript_text: If you wanna grow your triceps, you need to target the long head. All three heads will be hit during any movement involving elbow extension, but the position of your shoulder determines how the long head will be activated. If your arms are behind your torso on a tricep dip or kickback, you'll be training the long head in its shortened position. With your arms placed overhead, you'll be training the long head in its lengthened position. Lastly, something like a rope pushdown or skull crusher would be training the triceps through the middle of their range of motion. If you want to ensure all around development, it wouldn't be a bad idea to include at least one of each within your training weeks.

transcript_text: One thing about me is I always need to be progressing, and that really comes from a deep rooted fear of not being good enough. title: 3 Easy Steps To Fat Loss üìâ To drop body fat, you must consume fewer c...
description: 3 Easy Steps To Fat Loss üìâ To drop body fat, you must consume fewer calories than you burn daily. These three things make that reasonably simple to accomplish üëáüèª 1. Prioritize lifting over cardio - lifting builds and maintains muscle. The more muscle we have, the more calories we burn at rest, making it easier to stay in a deficit (+ you‚Äôll look better). If you‚Äôre dropping weight without lifting, you‚Äôll likely lose muscle. 2. Track your intake - this is the best way to ensure you‚Äôre in a deficit (& eating enough protein) without being overly restrictive with food. Aim for 300-500 calories below maintenance to start. There are plenty of online calculators to figure this out üëåüèª 3. Hit 8-10k steps daily - walking is the most underrated form of exercise and an almost effortless way to burn more calories. Add two 10-15 min walks into your day and try to get up & move around a little every hour. You can incorporate 3-5 15-20 min  cardio sessions into your week if needed, but make lifting the priority. I hope this helps some of you out ü§ôüèª ‚ûñ‚ûñ‚ûñ‚ûñ‚ûñ‚ûñ‚ûñ‚ûñ 1-1 online coaching üëâüèª link in bio #fitness #fatloss #cutting #onlinecoach #fatlosstips #nutrition #iifym #workout #workouttips

title: My favorite way to train chest üëáüèª In my experience, this is one of th...
description: My favorite way to train chest üëáüèª In my experience, this is one of the most efficient workouts you can do to maximize growth (of course, it‚Äôs not the only one). I average 8-12 sets per workout for chest 2x per week. Each rep focuses on controlling the weight, and I perform every set to failure. Here‚Äôs the explanation üëáüèª 1. Starting with 6-8 reps on an incline or flat machine press - this allows me to move heavy ass weight with an excellent mind-muscle connection since I don‚Äôt have to worry about stabilizing and minimizes the risk of injury. 2. I move on to 8-10 reps of incline or flat DB press - if I started with an incline, I‚Äôll do flat here & vice versa. As you get deeper into a workout, you can‚Äôt lift as heavy anyway, and I like the idea of not having to use as much weight on a riskier exercise. Plus, I notice I connect better vs. hitting it first. 3. Finish with a mid or high cable fly - this is based on the priority for the day. If I started with an incline press, I‚Äôd finish with a high/incline fly & vice versa. This is the final opportunity to gas out my chest, so I like to finish with partial reps at the end of each set üî• My first chest workout of the week is upper machine, flat db, high cable fly, and my second workout is the opposite. Then I‚Äôll finish up with front/side delts & triceps üëåüèª Try it out & let me know what you think üëäüèª ‚ûñ‚ûñ‚ûñ‚ûñ‚ûñ‚ûñ‚ûñ‚ûñ 1:1 Online Coaching üëáüèª Tap link in my bio to start your transformation #fitness #onlinecoach #chestworkout #aesthetics #workouttips #exercisetips #gains #buildmuscle

transcript_text: Let me tell you guys all the unhinged things I did to transform my body from this to what this is now. When I just started my fitness journey, it was super gym rat lifestyle all over TikTok and Instagram. I found out I had hypothyroidism, which just made things even harder for me. One week I'd lose two to three pounds and the next I'd gain around 7. My weight fluctuated a lot, but that didn't stop me. I knew that I could get to my goals. I just had to find the way that worked best for my body. First thing I had to do was to stop training like a man. Yeah, I said it now. Don't come for me. I still weight lift, but I don't weight lift more than 2 to 3 times a week. And I definitely don't when I'm close to my period or on my period. I'm not just exercising 2 to 3 times a week, but I do Pilates instead. And I'm not saying that Pilates is the miracle here. At the end of the day, it takes discipline, is low impact. It's not going to make you super tired or hungry. So it just made my diet a lot better. Hence why I reduced the amount of heavy lifting I was doing. And I decided to do something that I genuinely love. Not saying you need to do Pilates, but something low impact for you can definitely make a difference. I don't care if people get technical about it, but the mix of Pilates and strength training was just the right amount of exercise for me to feel good and not be burnt out. I know I'm going out to eat or to drink that night. Honestly, I eat a lot leaner during the day. It's just the truth. I will eat probably mainly protein and fiber, real super filling meals, but nothing too crazy so I can save a little bit more and enjoy a little bit more in the afternoon. Also, this might be weird, but I eat out a lot more than I do eat at home than most fitness influencers. I grew up loving to eat outside food and the only way I'm genuinely satisfied sometimes is going out and eating food outside of my home. They're the same way where you can't work unless you go to a cafe. And I'm gonna say it, I do have the same thing where I taste everything, eat nothing. I'm not actually eating nothing. It's just something I say. Because at the end of the day, you cannot eat that much. If you are short, not burning a bunch of calories throughout the day and want to be slim, comment down below if you want a little checklist of every single thing I do every week to stay on track.

description: Remember that all movement is GOOD movement! ‚ù§Ô∏è#xformer #megaformer #reformer #pilates #lagree
transcript_text: one of my biggest triggers as a certified Pilates instructor and now a certified X former instructor is when people say they're going to a reformer class when it is actually an X former or mega former yeah they're completely different things so I'm gonna break down what's the difference between all three of them and which one you should pick based on your goal starting with the earliest machine which is the reformer the traditional Pilates reformer created by Joseph Pilates himself in the 1920s it's a little bit on the smaller side it has a carriage it has springs a footbar headrest shoulder blocks and that's really about it physically you're going to improve your posture core strength and flexibility yes you will gain some strength in your body in your legs in your arms but it won't necessarily be a gain in mass aesthetically reformer work tends to create that long lean balanced body that Pilates is known for of course in a company with your diet now the Megaformer is the next one on this list this was made in the mid 2 this was created by Sebastian Lagree himself it is a larger version and instead of having a foot bar it has handle bars it has heavier springs and two platforms now this one is going to have a lot more endurance in there a little bit more of a strength training base so here is where mass starts to be built a little bit and where muscle failure will happen more and then the X former this is the newest form this was made in the twenty twenties it's fairly new and it's kind of a mixture of the reformer and the mega former it is a little bit bigger as well the cool thing about this one is that it has the addition to add cardio to it you can add burpees you can add mountain climbers you can add things like this to this workout to add a little bit of more cardio in there so you get the best of three worlds in here this one is going to give you a more athletic look a more gym fit but balanced look all around now you can totally do this on the reformer but as a beginner you're not gonna necessarily know how to adjust on the reformer or the mega reformer the springs neither one is better than the other I would highly suggest especially if you're a beginner it doesn't even matter which one of these you do at the beginning of your fitness journey you're going to feel different you're going to get stronger regardless I'm the one pick which one you like the most stick to that long as you can and if you wanna try other things try other things then it's really not that big of a deal

transcript_text: How to do belly hugs or 3 60 breathing during pregnancy? For starters, skip the chest breathing. It is so not effective. By the way, belly hugs or 3 60 breathing will aid in a quicker recovery, easier labor, and not to mention helps you move better with fewer pains during pregnancy. How to do it inhale into the belly, the sides of the ribs, and the back of the ribs expanding in all directions aka 360 degrees. Exhale slowly like you're blowing out a birthday candle. The belly should hug in and up and the navel should move towards the spine. This type of breathing utilizes the diaphragm and not the chest. Keep it breezy and beneficial.

transcript_text: Get ready with me while we talk about first trimester symptoms, food cravings, and food emergence. Beginning with symptoms, I would say that weeks 8 and 9 were the worst for me when it came down to pregnancy symptoms. I started to experience nausea around weeks seven or eightish, but it would usually go away around 4 p m. In the afternoon. And then one of my doctors told me about the amazing unisome and the six combo, and I took that for a few weeks throughout the tough parts of the first trimester, and I have to tell you, that saved me. I dealt a lot with insomnia in the first trimester. I'm still dealing with it. I get up at 3 or 4 a m. And then I can't fall back asleep until 6 or 7 a m. That's brutal. Food aversions. There is one silly little food that I just did not want anything to do with, and that was coffee. Which is crazy because I am such a coffee queen. I would have multiple throughout the day, and then around we ate, I just didn't want anything to do with coffee. I did had two major food cravings, and these cravings were consisted. I wanted them every day, and those were Honeycrisp apples and orange juice. All in all, I would say that the first trimester was pretty mild for me, but I was very consistent with my workouts. On the days I was working out, I would make sure that I got my 10K steps. I was good about hydrating and I was getting enough protein, and I feel like that really helped me power through, making sure that had enough energy and that I was able to keep moving. I'm gonna do one of those videos where you do the old wives tales about gender prediction, and this is the final look.

But what I realized was over time, with that perfect form and controlling the weight, I started seeing better results. I started getting stronger again cause I'd hit a plateau. Like that ego lifting in the beginning, especially if you're new to working out, it's a high risk, but you will get results. It's just that then you'll end up hitting a plateau. And so I was able to break that plateau by actually being willing to take a few steps back, using that proper form and controlling the weight. I was then able to surpass where I was at and hitting that plateau. If your form starts to break down, check the ego, use lighter weight that you can control. transcript_text: No.1, I need you to challenge yourself with your weight selection for the rep ranges that you're targeting. If you're trying to build strength, then that's where the super low volume reps with max weight is going to come into play. A lot of people think that when you're trying to put on a lot of size or you're bulking, you're going to do super low reps with a lot of weight. That's how you build strength. The way we want to build size and muscle mass is through hypertrophy. So I want to be strong and build muscle mass. So I still mix in some of those low rep ranges with max weight. But whether you're picking 10 or 20 reps, what I need you to do pick weight that is going to challenge you through that rep range. If you pick up a weight and you do 10 reps with it, and at your 10th rep, you had 10 more in the tank, you use too light a weight. I want you to use perfect form. And if your form starts to break down because you've picked too heavy of weight, you need to check your ego, and you need to go down in weight and maintain that perfect form. The proper range of motion is also going to be a major factor. Studies actually show a lot of the muscle stimulus is in the stretch portion, even though the contraction feels like that's where the majority Of the works being done, it's actually the majority. Instead of just using momentum to then try to force a contraction, especially if you like, I threw a bunch of weight on you. Use a lot of momentum right out of the gate to get it moving. transcript_text: After five years in corporate, I quit. In this episode of what I've Learned, I shared how courage brought me to the edge, but it was clarity that helped me take the leap. Hey, my name is Jean and I'm sure 90% of you who are watching this video thought about quitting your corporate job. To be Frank, I remember feeling constantly very drained and no matter how much rest I got, I still wake up feeling very tired. I thought perhaps I need a change of environment. So I went to another company to maybe bring that, but that did not last very long because one year later, I resigned. So here are some of the questions that I asked myself. Why did I want to leave? Was I running away from something or stepping towards something better? For me, it was about creating space to explore, to grow, to stop living on autopilot mode. But what about your financial situation? These are just a few things that I had to consider before I was leaving. For instance, rent. You have to ask yourself, how much rent are you paying for right now? Personally, I wouldn't leave unless I have about 3 to 6 months of caution for rent. Next, groceries. This might vary a lot depending on where you live and how you eat. Some questions you can ask yourself would be, what's your monthly grocery spend? And are you able to meal prep to cut costs? Followed By insurance, health insurance and travel insurance are very important as well. Other things that you might have to consider includes phone bills, utilities. And as for investment, are you going to continue investing or are you going to give it a pause and other little buffer of joy that you want in your life? In the next episode, I'll share where this leap has taken me and what this journey has taught me so far. So be sure to follow along and remember, stay curious.
